	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Apr 23rd 5:16 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.91]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Okay now here is a post i'm suprised hasn't been made before (at least i couldn't find one).<br><br>For those of you who don't know, quad kiting is when a druid uses his AoE DD spell combined with Snaring and 'tactical mob placement' (run in circles around them till their all in one 'spot') to kill 4 mobs at once. If you need to know more, look it up on Casters Realm strategies then come back here.<br><br>On this post i'm just addressing druid thoughts on BEGINING Quad Kiting. For this purpose assume i'm talking levels 34-40 or so. Maybe up to 44 is you think that still qualifies as 'begining' quad kiting.<br><br>Couple of ideas for replies...<br><br>1.) how important is evoc (or other if thats your opinion) spec. to quad kiting?<br><br>2.) where is the best quad kiting areas in these levels?<br><br>3.) what is the minimum level and or minimum wisdom you would consider/did/will quad kite at?<br><br>4.) how do you solve the problem if you go mana dead with the mobs not dead?<br><br><br><br>Alrighty folks. Reply to this and share your knowledge, opinoins, thoughts, dreams, etc, etc, etc with your fellow classmates.<br><br><br>(BTW if you all must know, my opinion is Icedlad is a great place to quad to learn, cougars are nice and can be feared in a pinch, i started around 35 but didn't feel comfortable till 37 or so, and my wisdom was about 174-178 in that time period.) (also Stonebrunt can be a good place to learn, try the south most zone wall)<br><br>(both places have the added benefit of being almost devoid of life if you play at the right time of day, and if you know where the zone line is and a mob isn't already stunning you, you can probably make it out in one piece)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
