	   <a name=101966844447225></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101966844447225><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101966844447225>RE: Begining Quad Kiting</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101966844447225#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=106454><span id= >Lunarwolf</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>18 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Apr 24th 1:20 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.78]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I started quadding with cougars in IC at about 35.&nbsp;&nbsp;My first attempt was at 34 and it went horribly wrong.  As a Wood Elf Druid with about 165 wis at 35, I only had a few problems with adds and lack of mana.  To combat the adds, you just have to be very careful of where you pull to, and you have to be very conscious of all the mobs in the distance that might be coming your way.  I recommend pulling the view back to one of the 3rd person views and looking around while you are waiting for the mobs to come into range.<br><br>For the mana, I believe it is possible to do this with even less wisdom.  Personally, I always sit and med between AoE's.  I generally run far enough away that I can sit and med for 1-2 ticks before the quad comes into range.  While that isnt a lot of mana at one time, I'm usually not in a big hurry to complete the quad, and over the course of an ensnare, Im usually able to get off one more AoE.  Also, don't forget that you can always re-ensnare before the spell breaks and continue the quad.<br><br>I don't know that I've seen a real advantage to having specialized in evocation.  On the other hand, I haven't had the chance to quad with a druid that has specialized in anything else.  Supposedly, with specialization, you have the chance to use less mana each time you cast a spell with that skill.  I haven't heard how much mana is saved or how often the specialization actually works.  So, now, I'm stuck in the opinion of, 'It can't hurt'.<br><br>I believe IC is the best place to quad at these levels.  I believe I remember getting 2 blues per quad at level 36.  The only problem is that if you get in trouble, you don't really have anywhere to run.  If you're having problems completing your quads at level 34 or 35, you might want to head over to GD and practice your Fear kiting on the dire wolves.  You have the added safety of dwarven guards if you get in trouble with these.  I haven't ever quadded in Stonebrunt due to the insane number of roaming mobs and the chance of an add.  I do think that SB is a great place to practice your charm kiting though.<br><br>Finally, what to do if you go oom with a mad, living quad.  This really depends on two things for me.  1) How long until ensnare runs out and 2) How much more would it take to kill the mob.  I have recently started using a clock near my computer to keep me informed of how long I have until my spells wear off.  If you are oom and your quad is going to be coming at you in just a few seconds, its time to get to a safe place as fast as you can.  Also, if you are oom and the quad has a lot of hps left, its time to go.  However, if you have enough time left on snare, simply run and med while keeping an eye on the group.  You can either med up enough mana to resnare the group and reset the clock, or if they are relatively low on hps, save the mana for a final AoE or two.<br><br>Quadding makes up a large part of a druids life after 34.  Currently, I get a little over a blue per quad at level 43.  I have about 7-8 minutes of downtime, and if all goes well, I generally make a little over a yellow per hour.<br><br>I hope this was helpful<br>-Lunar-<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
