	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101914243898596><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101914243898596>RE: Race?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101914243898596#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73409><span id=Scholar>Mistress ancarett</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>107 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Apr 18th 11:13 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.59]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Druids can be Half Elves, Halflings, Humans or Wood Elves. Each race has advantages and disadvantages. Wisdom is a stat you have to be concerned about with any druid: it is where you get your mana pool for spell-casting.<br><br>Halflings and Wood Elves are most common: they have the highest starting wisdom. Halflings also have very nice agility, dexterity and strength (though lousy charisma, so vendors will rip you off). Wood Elves are prettiest (can you tell I play one?) and have decent dexterity.<br><br>Half Elves have the worst starting wisdom but a lot of other decent statistics. Humans are pretty much in the middle (good all around) but lack night-vision. Fortunately, druids have a spell to summon a light source.<br><br>Most guides tell you to drop as many points as you can in wisdom (25) and then put the remaining points all into any of the following: strength (to hit harder and carry more), stamina (for more hitpoints), agility (to avoid being hit), dexterity (to hit more often), charisma (better prices from merchants and better success at charming animals).<br><br>A few guides will tell you NOT to put so much into wisdom, but they're expecting you to get a lot of gear from higher level characters (friends or your own). Only go this route if you KNOW you'll get those hand-me-downs and how they will help you.<br><br>Whatever you do, don't put point into intelligence. It is useless for a druid.<br><br>My choice? Wood Elf, 25 points into wisdom, 5 points into agility. Still happy, all these levels later.<br>&nbsp;<br>-- Ancarett, who lives at <a href="http://ancarett.com" target=_new>http://ancarett.com</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
